@Prev "Installation"
@Toc "Main"

@{b}Configuration of ASWPOP@{ub}
-----------------------

Right now then right now.. s:aswpop.prefs is the file that does the biz, it
holds all of the essential settings, so you're going to have go get your
fingers dirty with a bit of GED'ing.. (or CED if you're a CED kind of a
chap!).. right.. the layout of this file is pretty simple.. (Hey, PC owners
might buy Amigas and need a POP client in the future! :))  Basically, it's
the thing your configuring down the first column, and the setting down
number 2... get it yet? you change number 2! like so...

@{b}s:aswpop.config@{ub}
---------------

(All the following settings must be one word long, with the exception of
POSTPULL and PREPULL which can whole lines)

POPSERVER your.pop.mail.server
(your POP mail server.. ie.. mail.enterprise.net)

POPPORT 110
(this should do, leave it as it is!)

USERNAME your.username
(if you don't know your own POP account name, you need help!)

PASSWORD your.password
(same again!)

MAILBOX amitcp:usr/mail/andyw
(the mailbox where ASWPOP slings your mail by default)

ASWPOPPATH amitcp:aswpop
(the directory where ASWPOP looks for certain files used in operation.. did
 you remember it from earlier when I told you?! - Oh, and remember to omit
the trailing '/'!!)

STARTUPMODE CONTCHECK
(ASWPOP currently has 2 startup modes.. CONTCHECK and ONCE.. CONTCHECK
simply tells ASWPOP to check for mail, pause for a while, check for mail,
pause...until you break it.. ONCE makes ASWPOP check your box once, then
quit)

STARTUPMODEOPTS 2
(this is to define how long in minutes the pause between mailchecks in mode
CONTCHECK is...)

POSTPULL NONE
(ASWPOP can execute a command after pulling the mails and either being told
to exit, or after exiting after completing a ONCE startupmode check).. Enter
NONE or leave it blank for no command to be executed after quitting..

PREPULL NONE
(Exactly the same as POSTPULL, but executes the command on ASWPOP startup..)

MULTISERV
(If this is included in the prefs file, ASWPOP will look for a file in the
ASWPOP directory called aswpop.servers, (I'll describe the format of the
file a little later), and then will read through this list, checking each
server in turn, before reaching the end, pausing and quitting, if ASWPOP
is set to ONCE, or looping if set to CONTCHECK)

That is basically all you need to configure ASWPOP for basic mail retreival..
I'll go into configuring the more advanced features of ASWPOP a little later!

@{"Return to Installation " Link "Installation"} @{" Usage " Link "Usage"}

@Endnode

