@{b}Advanced ASWPOP'ing@{ub}
-------------------

Now.. this is when things get tough for a newbie to writing docs like me has
to finally get down and tackle the hard stuff! As I said, ASWPOP is very
powerful, and can be configured to execute scripts or perform functions such
as REDIRECT on incoming mails based on their From:, Subject: or To: lines..

Let's take a look at the file that holds the key, aswpop.acton

ADDRESS/SUBJECT - ACTION - OPTIONS

S ASWPOP REDIRECT uumail:aswpop
A aminetd@wuarchive.wustl.edu REDIRECT uumail:aminet-daily
A user@wilmington05.voicenet.com KILL
A you@are.a.fuckwit.com KILL
S ircmsg EXTERN amitcp:aswpop/aswpex.ircmsg NOWRITE
S test INTERN amitcp:aswpop/aswpin.autorep
S ftpmail EXTERN amitcp:aswpop/aswpex.ftpmail FILENAME NOWRITE

The single letter that begins each line tells ASWPOP what the field to search
*IS*, beit S (Subject) A (From address) or T (To address)

Basically, the second word is the From:, Subject: or To: line to scan
for.. the third is the ACTON type and anything after and including the
fourth word become the ACTON type arguments.. If a message matches more than
one ACTON preference, then both/all ACTON's will be executed.

@{b}ACTON types@{ub}
-----------

@{b}REDIRECT@{ub} - When a match on a mail that has an REDIRECT acton
assigned to it, ASWPOP routes the email to an alternative mailbox
that is specified in word 4...

@{b}KILL@{ub} - Ever had an annoying turd never giving your mailbox a
break? Some tosser constantly sending you drivel? Enter the KILL acton! :)
On encountering a message that hits a KILL match, ASWPOP informs you that
you're not going to see that email.. and you won't! hehe

@{b}HIGHLIGHT@{ub} - This function simply beeps your display and tells you
that an important email has come in... useful if you're busy IRC'ing or
something, and expecting an important mail in!

@{b}INTERN@{ub} - This is a BIG feature of ASWPOP.. it allows you to execute
a chunk of rexx source held externally in a file when a matched email comes
in.. The advantage here is that it's run internally as if it was ASWPOP
code, therefore giving you all the system variables at your fingertips.. a
useful selection of those being:

NUM_MSG - The total number of messages the remote POP server had waiting for
          you at the point ASWPOP was run.
OPTIONS - The options given after word 4 in the ACTON file.
WRITEMAIL - Should ASWPOP write the mail to the default box or not? (must be
            YES or NO) (default is NO when an INTERN acton is called)
MSGNO - The current message number
ADDY - The From: address of the current message
SUBJ - The Subject of the current message
DATEY - The Date of the current message
MSGSIZE.(1 to highest message number) - The sizes of all the waiting mails
        are stored in MSGSIZE. arrays.. eg.. MSGSIZE.1 = The size of email
        number 1

I have included an example INTERN script in this distribution.. it's playful
purpose is to automatically return a mail to the sender.. Any valid AREXX
script that doesn't conflict with the Open files etc of ASWPOP will work..
I must say however, that if ASWPOP refuses to work with an INTERN acton
script, then it's the script that's bad! The possible uses of an INTERN
script don't stop at the silly.. for example, it seems quite possible for a
user to write many a useful tool... A Mailing list processor, FTPmail
system, a email->command execution system, File request server... as you can
see, the possibilties are quite exciting!!

To set up an INTERN acton, write your script, and append a line like the
following into aswpop.acton:

S craplist INTERN amitcp:bin/craplist.rx

S (set scan for Subject mode)
craplist (subject or address to search for)
INTERN (INTERN acton type is to be used when the subject/address is matched
       with the current email)
amitcp:bin/craplist.rx (full path to the rexx script)

@{b}EXTERN@{ub}

The EXTERN acton works in a similar fashion to the INTERN type, apart from
it can call anything that can be run.. quite simply, it runs the Option line
when matching an email's particulars.. when an EXTERN acton is executed,
some files are created in ENV: that may be of some use:

env:from, env:subj and env:date - I shouldn't have to tell you what they
contain! :-) Oh, and the current email is in a free to read/write file,
t:poptemp..

Also, 2 special keywords can be placed in the OPTIONS line when using the
EXTERN type.. NOWRITE and FILENAME...

NOWRITE will tell ASWPOP not to write the email to the default mailbox and..
FILENAME will replace itself with the path to the temporary email storage
file..

All externally executed commands must return to the CLI prompt before ASWPOP
will continue..

Possible uses of the EXTERN type include:

Making the miggy shout out when a mail from someone comes in!:

A andyw@enterprise.net EXTERN c:playasound dh2:ohmygod.snd

Bringing up the mail in a text reader and not writing it to the mailbox:

A andyw@enterprise.net EXTERN c:readit FILENAME NOWRITE

Or, as with INTERN, you can write your own Arexx scripts (but this time, you
won't have access to the operational variables) or Dos scripts and run them
from an EXTERN match.. I have included a dodgy FTPmail server EXTERN script
as an example.. don't expect it to work though! I've hardly touched the
thing, but it's a start!

@{b}NOTE@{ub}

If ASWPOP fails to work after running an INTERN or EXTERN script/command,
then it IS the script/command that is fouling the system up.. if you can't
resolve the problem, then I'll be glad to help with it.

@{b}Setting up ASWPOP for multi server checking@{ub}

If you have more than 1 POPmail account, ASWPOP can be told to check all of
them in sequence, on it's own. Simply add MULTISERV in the aswpop.prefs
file, and create a file in the ASWPOP dir called aswpop.servers, the format
of this file is as follows:

<server name> <login> <password> <mailbox>... ie..

mail.enterprise.net andyw secret uumail:andyw
mail.othernet.net hello passwd uumail:fishy

Simply set it up like this, and run ASWPOP in the normal way.. the log file
will keep you informed on what server it is connected to.


